>
  <p>Picking <strong>web hosting for a small business</strong> isn't about finding the single "best" host — it's about matching a provider to what your business actually does online. A local shop with a brochure site has very different needs from a studio running an online store. This guide walks through the criteria that matter so you can judge any provider for yourself, rather than trust a leaderboard or a discount banner.</p>

  <h2>Start from what your site needs to do</h2>
  <p>Before comparing plans, write down the job your site has to do. Most small-business sites fall into one of a few shapes, and the shape decides the hosting:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Brochure / presence site</strong> — a few pages, contact form, maybe a blog. Light, mostly static, low traffic. Modest hosting is plenty.</li>
    <li><strong>Lead-generation site</strong> — forms, booking, a CMS like WordPress. Needs reliable uptime and decent support more than raw power.</li>
    <li><strong>Online store</strong> — a shop platform, a database, checkout. Needs consistent performance, backups, and headroom for traffic peaks.</li>
    <li><strong>Custom app</strong> — a bespoke tool or membership area. Often outgrows shared hosting and wants a VPS with full control.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Sizing to the job keeps you from overpaying for a server you don't need — or, worse, from picking a plan that buckles the first time you get busy.</p>

  <h2>The criteria that actually matter</h2>

  <h3>Reliability and uptime</h3>
  <p>If the site is down, it can't sell or capture leads. Look for a published <strong>uptime SLA</strong> (a concrete commitment) rather than vague "99.9%-ish" marketing. Reliability comes from the infrastructure and the network, not from the price tier — cheap doesn't have to mean flaky, but unmaintained does.</p>

  <h3>Support you can actually reach</h3>
  <p>When you don't have an in-house IT person, support <em>is</em> your IT department. Check the channels (chat, ticket, phone), the hours, and the languages. For a business, support that answers quickly during your working day is worth more than a slightly cheaper plan with email-only replies.</p>

  <h3>Performance and speed</h3>
  <p>Slow pages lose customers and rank worse in search. The practical levers are <strong>SSD/NVMe storage</strong>, enough memory and CPU for your platform, and a <strong>server location near your customers</strong> — physical distance adds latency to every request. A CDN can speed up static assets, but the origin still matters for dynamic pages and checkout.</p>

