  <h3>Email and domain</h3>
  <p>A professional address on your own domain (you@yourbusiness.com) builds trust far better than a free webmail address. Check whether business email is bundled, an add-on, or expected to come from a separate provider. Confirm you can register or transfer your domain, and that you keep control of it.</p>

  <h3>Security</h3>
  <p>At minimum you want a <strong>free TLS certificate</strong> (HTTPS), automatic platform updates where the host manages them, and sensible firewalling. For sites handling customer data or payments, ask about isolation and how the host responds to incidents. Security you have to bolt on yourself is a hidden cost.</p>

  <h3>Backups and recovery</h3>
  <p>Mistakes, bad updates and attacks happen. <strong>Automated, regular backups</strong> with an easy one-click restore are worth paying for — they turn a disaster into a five-minute fix. Confirm how far back backups go and whether restoring is self-service or a support request.</p>

  <h3>Room to grow</h3>
  <p>The plan that fits today should let you scale up without a painful migration. Can you upgrade resources, move from shared hosting to a VPS, or add storage on demand? Picking a provider with a clear upgrade path means your first move online isn't a dead end.</p>

  <h3>Honest pricing</h3>
  <p>Compare the <em>renewal</em> price, not just the promotional first term — intro rates often jump at renewal. Confirm what's bundled (email, TLS, backups, domain) versus billed separately. The cheapest sticker price frequently excludes things you'll end up buying anyway.</p>

  <h2>Shared hosting vs VPS for a small business</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Question</th><th>Shared hosting</th><th>VPS</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Setup &amp; upkeep</td><td>Managed for you, minimal effort</td><td>More control, more responsibility (unless managed)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Performance</td><td>Shared with neighbours on the server</td><td>Dedicated, guaranteed resources</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Custom software</td><td>Limited to what the host allows</td><td>Full root access, install anything</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Best for</td><td>Brochure &amp; small CMS sites</td><td>Stores, custom apps, steady traffic</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Many businesses start on shared hosting and move to a <strong>VPS</strong> once traffic, a database-heavy store, or a custom stack outgrows it. A VPS gives you dedicated RAM and CPU plus full control of the environment — the right step up when shared hosting starts to pinch. Providers like <strong>Contabo</strong> are known for offering generous CPU and RAM at a reasonable price, which makes a VPS a realistic option even for a small budget.</p>

  <h2>Who it's for</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>A brochure or local-business site</strong> → managed shared hosting with good support, email and backups. Keep it simple.</li>
    <li><strong>A growing store or lead-gen site</strong> → prioritise uptime, performance and automated backups; plan an upgrade path.</li>
    <li><strong>A custom app or a store with steady traffic</strong> → a VPS for dedicated resources and full control.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>How to decide</h2>
  <p>Define the job your site does, then weight the criteria accordingly: a store leans on performance and backups, a brochure site leans on simplicity and support. Insist on a real uptime commitment, reachable support, HTTPS, automated backups and a server near your customers — and compare renewal prices on equivalent specs. Pick the smallest plan that covers your real workload with a little headroom and a clear path to upgrade, and you'll have hosting that grows with the business instead of holding it back.</p>
